problem_statement.RootCause:
1) LogisticRegressionCV.fit resolves the effective multiclass strategy into a local variable multi_class near the start of the method (sklearn/linear_model/logistic.py:2004–2005):
   multi_class = _check_multi_class(self.multi_class, solver, len(classes))
   The resolved local multi_class is then passed into the path function that builds fold_coefs_ (sklearn/linear_model/logistic.py:2062) and is used to reshape coefs_paths according to the chosen strategy (see the multinomial vs else reshaping at lines 2086–2113).

2) Later, in the refit=False branch of LogisticRegressionCV.fit, the code decides which indexing pattern to use to average coefficients across folds using the instance attribute self.multi_class instead of the resolved local multi_class (sklearn/linear_model/logistic.py:2172–2178):
   best_indices = np.argmax(scores, axis=1)
   if self.multi_class == 'ovr':
       w = np.mean([coefs_paths[i, best_indices[i], :]
                    for i in range(len(folds))], axis=0)
   else:
       w = np.mean([coefs_paths[:, i, best_indices[i], :]
                    for i in range(len(folds))], axis=0)

   Because coefs_paths was constructed according to the resolved local multi_class, using self.multi_class (which may be the user-supplied value 'auto') can cause the code to pick the indexing pattern that does not match the actual shape of coefs_paths. For example, when self.multi_class == 'auto' but the resolved multi_class == 'ovr' (typical for binary classification), the else (multinomial-style) indexing is taken even though coefs_paths has the OvR shape; attempting to index the array with the multinomial indexing pattern triggers IndexError: "too many indices for array".

3) The mismatch is localized to the refit=False averaging branch described above. Other parts of the method (including the refit=True branch and the earlier construction/reshape of coefs_paths) use the resolved local multi_class consistently.
